{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17608803","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17608803"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:36:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:36:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16045"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16045","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16045"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0,0.53,0.41,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8736"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67284"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8736","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8736"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16045"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52736"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4693"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7567"},{"type":"tags","id":"9616"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20892"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20899"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22529"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67284","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67284"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA man is having a routine physical examination when the practitioner notes something different about his right hand (Image). The patient says that his hand has always had that appearance.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the anomaly?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Amelia","Meromelia","Preaxial polydactyly","Postaxial polydactyly","Syndactyly"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMeromelia\u003C/strong\u003E refers to partial absence of a limb, while \u003Cstrong\u003Eamelia\u003C/strong\u003E describes complete absence of a limb. \u003Cstrong\u003EPostaxial polydactyly\u003C/strong\u003E specifically refers to extra digits on the ulnar (little finger) side of the hand or lateral side of the foot. \u003Cstrong\u003ESyndactyly\u003C/strong\u003E is the fusion of adjacent digits. \u003Cstrong\u003EPreaxial polydactyly\u003C/strong\u003E refers to extra digits on the radial (thumb) side of the hand.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPostaxial polydactyly is the most common form of polydactyly. It may occur as an isolated finding or as part of a genetic syndrome. The extra digit can range from a small, soft tissue appendage to a fully formed finger with normal skeletal elements. The prevalence of polydactyly is about 1;1,000 and seen twice as often in males than females.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Preaxial polydactyly refers to extra digits on the radial (thumb) side of the hand.","Polydactyly is one of the most common congenital limb differences, occurring in approximately 1 in 1000 live births."],"references":["Kyriazis Z, Kollia P, Grivea I, Stefanou N, Sotiriou S, Dailiana ZH. Polydactyly: Clinical and molecular manifestations. World J Orthop. 2023 Jan 18;14(1):13-22. doi: 10.5312/wjo.v14.i1.13. PMID: 36686282; PMCID: PMC9850794.","Bubshait DK. A review of polydactyly and its inheritance: Connecting the dots. Medicine (Baltimore). 2022 Dec 16;101(50):e32060. doi: 10.1097/MD.0000000000032060. PMID: 36550802; PMCID: PMC9771235.","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science","Singh, V. (2022). Textbook of clinical embryology, -E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52736"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16045"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21288"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21288","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21288"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/KuYEkQCwCEULWhYICsFUNqWgeWHxbv.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/KuYEkQCwCEULWhYICsFUNqWgeWHxbv.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":423,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52736","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52736"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-04T17:17:18+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-04T17:18:05+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8736"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67284"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"34","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/34"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Orthopaedics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"headi